1. Nc3 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 d5 4. d4 e6 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. dxc5 Na6 8. Na4 Qa5 { %02 [ ? Unnecessarily complicating the c-P issue. Simply  8...Nxc5 9.Nxcx5 Bxc5 =. ] } 9. c4 dxc4 { %02 [ ?? Still 9...Nxc5 10.Nxc5 Qxc5 =. ] } 10. Bd2 Qd8 { [ ? If 10...Qb5 11.Nd4 Qd7 12.c6! Qxd4 13.cxb7 Rb8 14.bxc8Q Rfxc8 15.Bc3! $16, but this may be better than the text.] } 11. c6 { [ ! If now 11...bc 12.Ne5 $16. Black's comfort level has now disappeared. ] } b5 12. Nc3 Qb6 { %02 [ Or 12... Nc7 13.Bf4 $18. ] } 13. a4 { [ ! Busting up Black's Ps for easy targets. ] } b4 14. Nb5 Nc7 15. Be3 Qa5 16. Ne5 { %02 [ ! Winning material ultimately. ] } Nxb5 17. Nxc4 Qa6 18. axb5 Qxb5 19. Nb6 { %02 [ ! The point, the a-P is won. ] } Rb8 20. Nxc8 Rbxc8 21. Rxa7 Bc5 22. Qa4 { %02 [ ! Permits White to retain the dreadful c-P. ] } Qxa4 23. Rxa4 Bxe3 24. fxe3 Nd5 25. Rc1 Rfe8 26. Kf2 Kf8 27. Bxd5 exd5 28. Rxb4 Re6 29. Rd4 { [ ? Giving Black a little hope, stronger is 29. Rb6 followed by b4 and b5. ] } Rf6+ { + } 30. Ke1 Rfxc6 31. Rxc6 Rxc6 32. b4 { %02 [ Interesting, he prefers not to grab 32.Rxd5 Rb6 33.Rd2 Rb3, because his R would be passive. ] } Rb6 33. Kd2 Ke7 34. Kc3 Ke6 35. g4 { %02 [ ! Prevents 35... f5. ] } Ke5 36. Kb3 Rh6 { %02 [ White's b-P will advance no matter what, so Black does not hesitate to plunder. ] } 37. b5 Rxh2 38. b6 Kd6 { [ Or 38...Rxe2 39.Rb4 Rxe3+ 40.Kc2 Kd6 41.b7, the same as the text. ] } 39. Rb4 Rxe2 40. b7 Rxe3+ { + } 41. Kc2 Re8 42. b8=Q+ { + } Rxb8 43. Rxb8 Ke5 44. Rb7 Kf6 45. Kd3 g6 46. Rb5 Kg5 { %02 [ Or 46...Ke5 47.g5. ] } 47. Rxd5+ { + } Kxg4 48. Rd7 h5 49. Rxf7 h4 50. Ke2 Kg3 51. Kf1 Kh2 52. Kf2 g5 53. Kf3 Kh3 54. Rg7 Kh2 55. Rxg5 h3 56. Kf2 Kh1 57. Ra5 Kh2 58. Ra3 { %02 Black resigns. } 1-0

